#scatter chart

sns.set_style("white")

plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

sns.lmplot(data=df, x="petal_width", y="petal_length", hue="flower_name", palette="mako", height=10, legend=False)
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), loc='best', fontsize=20)
Out[24]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7f846e758940>
<Figure size 720x720 with 0 Axes>

 Exploration Interpretation:

This exploration represents the scatter chart associated with the regression line. The regression line plays a vital role in identifying the outliers and the general estimate of the model residuals "errors". Outliers are the observations that have extreme values. Ususally outliers might come with an idea of eliminating them, but that's not true, anomalies need to be detected and studied as they might reflect real type of observations. Usually we start with the hypothesis testing in favor of anomaly detection.

When it comes to the residual rates, it's another factor that reflects the accuracy of our model, especially while prediction.

For this chart, the best values that are spread around the regression line just like the flower Versicolor, unlike the Virignica flower that most of the values are quite abroad from the regression line which gives the residual rate to increase.

The basic equation for regression is:

(Yi) > Dependent value (Xi) > Independent value Intercept > Beta, and the residual.

Yi = Intercept + Beta * Xi + E "E stands for the Error factor".

# https://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.pairplot.html


 Exploration Interpretation:

This exploration is one of the best visualisation individual can use while building a model. It gives everything in one place, so let's get started:

- The pairwise is a combination between a single variable exploration "The histograms" where they represent the variable intersection with itself and shows the distribution.

- The rest of the plots are scatter charts where they highlight the interaction between the two variables, promising analysis can be made such as finding the corelation coefficient if one of the scatter plots draw close attention.

That's in general, but what can be gained from the Iris dataset pairwise plot?

- If we look at the histogram of the petal length with itself we can see that Setosa type is skewed right on the other hand we find that both Versicolor and Virginca species are skewed left. Same with the petal width histogram in the last plot of the pairwise. 

- Right skewed means the observations are small. And left skewed means the observations are medium/or even large.

In [30]:
# Create a loop to execute the code on the whole dataset.

centers = {}

for i in range(3):
    output_array = []
    output_array.append(df.loc[df['flower_name'] == i]["petal_width"].mean())
    output_array.append(df.loc[df['flower_name'] == i]["petal_length"].mean())
    
    centers[i] = output_array
In [31]:
# Plotting the 3 clusters with the centroids

sns.set_style("white")
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))


exploration = sns.scatterplot(data=df, x="petal_width", y="petal_length", hue = "flower_name", palette = "coolwarm", s=100)

colors = {0 : 'red', 1: 'blue', 2: 'orange'}
for i in range(3):
    plt.scatter(centers[i][0], centers[i][1], color  = colors[i], s=220, marker="$\circ$")

plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1), title='Flower Name', loc='upper left', 
           labels=[{'red' : 'Setosa'},{'blue' : 'Versicolor'} , {'orange' :'Virginica'}], fontsize=12)


plt.show(exploration)


 Exploration Interpretation:

In the next section, it's about the last point of step one which is the plotting the 3 clusters.

Since the clustering is unsupervised learning I have converted the categorical column "flower name" into cluster from 0 to 2. Then I have used the scatter chart to visualize it and finally I wanted to highlight the centroids for each specie. Finally I made sure that the legend interpret the values correctly.

import numpy as np
 
# initializing points in numpy arrays
# Basically I took the first 6 rows and convert them into arrays.

point1 = np.array((3,3.2,3.1,3.6,3.9,3.4))
point2 = np.array((4.9,4.7,4.6,5,5.4,4.6))
 
# finding sum of squares

sum_sq = np.sum(np.square(point1 - point2))
 
# Doing squareroot and
# printing Euclidean distance

print("The value of the Euclidean Distance is:", round(np.sqrt(sum_sq), 2))

The value of the Euclidean Distance is: 3.71

Step Three: Acknowledging The Question

¶

How do you interpret your dendrogram? how many species does it show?¶

Manually, I have first calculated the distance matrix as given in the next images where I have used the first 6 rows then divide every values that are in the same column. After creating the distance matrix, it becomes easier to plot the scatter chart and highlight the data points. Once completed this step I was able to draw the dedrogram.

On the other hand, via code it was a couple of lines and generated the visualisation as the techniques such as Single linkage algorithms or the euclidean distance have functions and library for such a matter.

It shows 4 clusters, three of these clusters contains dual data points (or small clusters) and one circle them all.

The number of species showed by the dendrogram are 3 species.
